14 WHEREAS, it is in the State's best interest to ensure that data collection and reporting
15 processes comply with the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and
16 other relevant regulations; and
17 WHEREAS, penalties and enforcement mechanisms need to be assessed to ensure
18 compliance with reporting requirements while minimizing the administrative burden on
19 healthcare providers; and
20 WHEREAS, it would be beneficial to:
21 (1) Evaluate the impact of healthcare reporting on Medicaid care management
22 organizations and healthcare providers;
23 (2) Assess the effectiveness of data integration between clinical and claims records in
24 measuring healthcare quality;
25 (3) Examine best practices for implementing healthcare reporting and ensuring compliance
26 among participating entities;
27 (4) Investigate the role of statewide healthcare data initiatives in supporting reporting
28 efforts;
29 (5) Consider the implications of penalties and enforcement measures on Medicaid care
30 management organizations and insurers; and
31 (6) Ensure that healthcare providers are not unduly burdened with costs or administrative
32 requirements related to compliance with reporting mandates.
33 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
34 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
35 on Healthcare Quality and Reporting.
36 (2) Members and officers.
37 (A) The committee shall be composed of nine members.
